Available online 20 July 2025 Article Developing a stable and high-performance W-CoMnP electrocatalyst by mitigating the Jahn-Teller effect through W doping strategy Bohan An a b Xin Li a b Weilong Liu a b Jipeng Dong a b Ruichao Bian a b Luyao Zhang a b Ning Li a b Yangqin Gao a b Lei Ge a b * a State Key Laboratory of Heavy Oil Processing, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China State Key Laboratory of Heavy Oil Processing College of New Energy and Materials China University of Petroleum Beijing Beijing 102249 China State Key Laboratory of Heavy Oil Processing, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China b Department of Materials Science and Engineering, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China Department of Materials Science and Engineering College of New Energy and Materials China University of Petroleum Beijing Beijing 102249 China Department of Materials Science and Engineering, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China * Corresponding author Manganese-based materials are influenced by the Jahn-Teller effect, causing the spontaneous dismutation of Mn3+ (2Mn3+ → Mn2+ + Mn4+) and the dissolution of Mn2+, which often results in diminished activity. This study uniquely employs a W doping strategy to suppress this effect. Externally, a simple template-free method was initially used to prepare cobalt- and manganese-based precursors, followed by a W doping process during the synthesis of transition bimetallic phosphides. Ultimately, W-doped bimetallic phosphides (W-CoMnP) were obtained. The W-CoMnP material demonstrates excellent HER and OER performance with low overpotentials of 95 mV (η₁₀ HER) and 225 mV (η₅₀ OER), and can achieve overall water splitting at a voltage of 1.52 V while maintaining stable cycling for 24 h. To enable commercial application, W-CoMnP was incorporated into an anion exchange membrane (AEM) electrolysis water device, demonstrating continuous and stable hydrogen production under ambient temperature conditions. This study offers a promising strategy for the future development of catalysts for AEM electrolysis water devices. Graphical Abstract A simple and effective strategy was developed to reduce the Jahn-Teller effect and improve the electrocatalytic performance of Mn-based catalysts. W-MnCoP has the ability of a bifunctional catalyst and can achieve stable operation at 1.52 V for 24 h. Keywords Bimetallic phosphide Density functional theory calculation Jiang-Taylor effect W doping Anion exchange membrane water electrolysis device 1 Introduction The urgent need to explore clean and sustainable energy stem from the increasingly serious energy problem and the environmental damage caused by excessive use of fossil fuels [ 1–3 ]. Hydrogen has many advantages, including zero pollution emissions and higher utilization efficiency, and is considered one of the most promising alternative fuels to traditional fossil fuels [ 4 ]. Hydrogen is a remarkable energy carrier. The most widely used hydrogen production process is hydrocarbon reforming [ 5,6 ]. However, the disadvantage of this method is that burning fossil fuels releases a large amount of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere [ 6 ]. The electrochemical water splitting using solar energy and industrial surplus electricity provides an effective way to produce high-purity hydrogen gas due to its efficient use of energy and environmental protection concept [ 7–9 ]. Electrolysis of water to produce hydrogen can be divided into cathodic hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) and anodic oxygen evolution reaction (OER) [ 10 ]. However, during the experimental process, due to the 4-electron reaction involved in OER, the reaction was slow, severely limiting the practical application of electrochemical water splitting [ 10–12 ]. In order to improve the huge reaction barrier of OER in the electrolysis process and ensure the smooth progress of the HER reaction, the development of efficient bifunctional catalysts has become a research hotspot for electrolysis water catalysts. At present, membrane water electrolysis (WE) systems, such as proton exchange membranes (PEM) and anion exchange membranes (AEM), have become a popular field for hydrogen production through electrolysis of water due to their compact and sustainable hydrogen production processes, which meet the requirements of economic commercialization [ 13–15 ]. AEM technology has significant potential for application in energy storage and conversion, especially in the fields of hydrogen energy and fuel cells. Compared with traditional proton exchange membranes (PEM), AEM exhibits superior characteristics in the following key aspects [ 16–19 ]: (1) Cost reduction: Traditional proton exchange membrane fuel cells typically use expensive precious metal catalysts such as platinum, while AEM can use non precious metal catalysts such as nickel, cobalt, etc. at lower temperatures, significantly reducing the system's cost. Therefore, AEM technology can help promote the commercialization of hydrogen fuel cells, especially in cost sensitive application scenarios. (2) Improve energy efficiency: Compared to PEM batteries, AEM batteries are typically able to operate over a wider pH range, which allows AEM to use alkaline media. This not only helps improve the efficiency of the battery, but also expands its application range, including working in some extreme environments. (3) Supporting renewable energy: Due to the stable operation of AEM batteries in highly alkaline environments, it provides a new solution for the storage and conversion of renewable energy, especially in the storage of volatile energy sources such as solar and wind energy. AEM technology offers new possibilities. Based on the above advantages, it can be concluded that. As a trend in future technological development, AEM (Anion Exchange Membrane) has broad application prospects and unique advantages. It has enormous potential for application in energy conversion, environmental protection and sustainable development, which can reduce costs, improve efficiency, support the development of green energy and help solve global environmental problems. With the advancement of materials science, catalyst technology and battery technology, the performance and application areas of AEM will continue to expand, becoming one of the important directions for future development. To achieve future hydrogen production through water electrolysis, many studies focus research on AEM systems, and a feasible AEM system must operate under optimized battery voltage, current density and temperature conditions. In addition, it is necessary to consider attenuation issues during the preparation process, such as damage to AEM components (such as membranes and catalysts) under harsh operating conditions; Especially the deactivation of catalysts, severe damage to surface atomic structure and composition leading to catalyst deactivation and lower AEM efficiency [ 15 ]. The ideal catalyst should maintain stability under thermodynamic and electrochemical (EC) conditions, as well as acidic or alkaline conditions [ 20 ]. For long-term steady-state catalysis, precious metal materials such as RuO2 [ 21 ], Pt [ 22 ], IrO2 [ 23 ] etc. with high catalytic activity are often selected in industry. However, the production of these precious metal-based catalysts is scarce, resulting in high costs and hindering their widespread commercialization [ 20 ]. In addition, traditional metal-based materials cannot exhibit significant electrolyte activity for both HER and OER simultaneously, resulting in low energy utilization efficiency and high manufacturing costs. Therefore, developing efficient, low-cost and stable bifunctional catalysts has become an inevitable research trend [ 24,25 ]. At present, due to the unique Pt like electronic structure and cost-effectiveness of transition metal phosphides (TMPs) as well as their inherent HER and OER catalytic activity, they can be used as electrocatalysts for overall water splitting [ 26 ]. Among numerous transition metal phosphides (TMPs), cobalt based TMP catalysts such as CoP and Co2P [ 27 ] have attracted the attention of numerous researchers due to their low overpotential and good stability. However, considering further practical applications, the electrolytic water performance of cobalt based TMP still needs further improvement. To resolve this situation, Co based materials combine with Mn elements to form CoMnP nanostructures, which exhibit high catalytic activity by reducing their size and uniformly dispersing [ 28 ]. However, the inherent Jahn Teller effect of Mn based materials leads to spontaneous dismutation reaction of Mn3+(2Mn3+ → Mn2+ + Mn4+) and dissolution of Mn2+, ultimately resulting in structural deterioration and decreased activity [ 29–31 ]. These disadvantages are particularly severe in electrocatalytic performance. To solve the above problems, the W doping method can be adopted to suppress the Jahn Teller effect. In addition, W is considered the best ideal promoter for improving the catalytic performance of electrocatalysts, as it can generate a large number of free charge carriers near Fermi level to regulate electron orbits, thereby possessing excellent charge transfer ability. Therefore, doping W into TMPs is expected to become a profitable challenge for achieving electron redistribution, which can help improve material performance at high current densities. In this study, W-doped bimetallic phosphides were designed and synthesized from the MOF structure to achieve precise synergistic effects of charge modulation and electron redistribution. The bimetallic center leads to a significant improvement in catalytic performance. Specifically, a CoMn precursor doped with W was obtained through a one-step solvothermal epitaxial growth process. Finally, W-doped bimetallic phosphides were prepared using in-situ phosphorization strategy. The phase conjugation of two metal phosphides and the synergistic effect of metal centers have a regulatory effect on electronic distribution, while exhibiting a larger specific surface area and exposing more active sites. Jahn Teller effect was successfully suppressed. W-CoMnP material has excellent HER and OER activity, exhibiting low overpotentials of 95 mV (η 10, HER) and 225 mV (η 50, OER), and can achieve overall water splitting at a voltage of 1.52 V as well as stable cycling for 24 h. The W-CoMnP material was assembled into AEM electrolysis water device, and continuous and stable hydrogen production can be achieved under normal temperature conditions. Detailed theoretical research and calculation results also demonstrate that the synergistic effect between Mn and Co ions can effectively reduce the energy barrier in the rate determining step (RDS), thereby improving the catalytic activity and reducing the OER activation energy (E a). 2 Experimental 2.1 Synthesis of W-CoMn precursor All compounds are purchased and used directly without additional purification. Firstly, add 5 mmol (1.25 g) of cobalt acetate tetrahydrate, 5 mmol (0.63 g) of anhydrous manganese chloride, and 5 mmol (0.3 g) of urea, and stir rapidly in 60 mL of ethanol. After the powder dissolves, add 0.02 g of ammonium metatungstate and continue stirring. Keep the mixture at room temperature for 24 h. Then heat the solution to 90 °C and maintain it at that temperature for 10 h, collect the blue powder, and dry it in a vacuum drying oven at 70 °C for 12 h. The blue powder is a precursor of W-CoMn (Fig. S1), The SEM and TEM images of W-CoMn Precursor are shown in Fig. S2. 2.2 Synthesis of W-CoMnP catalyst The W-CoMn precursor and NaH2PO2·H2O are placed at both ends of the pipeline equipment in a ratio of 1:10, with NaH2PO2·H2O located on the upstream side. The experimental phosphating process is as follows: under continuous protective gas conditions, the temperature is maintained at 400 °C, the heating rate is maintained at 2 °C/min, and the duration is 2 h. Finally, the prepared sample was repeatedly washed with alcohol (CH3CH2OH) to remove unreacted substances and impurities. Finally, the sample was dried overnight in a vacuum environment to obtain the target catalyst W-CoMnP. In the next step, 5 mg of the target sample (presumably W-CoMnP electrode material), 40 μL Nafion (5 wt%) and 960 μL alcohol were ultrasonic mixed. After obtaining a uniform mixture, the mixture droplets of 10 μL were applied to the clean conductive glass surface. After the solution was dried, the resulting product was W-CoMnP Electrodes. The coating area on the conductive glass was determined to be 1 × 1 cm2, the calculated loading capacity should be approximately 0.05 mg/cm2. 2.4 Characterizations The crystallographic characterization of all samples was investigated by X-ray diffractometer (XRD) (Cu-Kα radiation, λ = 1.5406 Å) with a 2θ range of 10° to 90° and a scan rate of 5° min-1. Samples doped with tungsten can enhance the sustainability of OER through the following three strategies [ 43–48 ]: (1) Enhanced catalytic activity: Tungsten is a transition metal with high electronegativity and strong chemical stability, which gives it excellent electron transfer ability in catalytic reactions. The addition of tungsten can improve the electronic structure of the catalyst, thereby enhancing its catalytic activity for OER reaction. The addition of tungsten usually affects the valence band and conductivity of the material, allowing the catalyst to more effectively promote the generation of oxygen molecules; (2) Improve stability: OER is a complex reaction involving multiple electron transfers, which is often accompanied by corrosion and degradation of the catalyst. Tungsten has strong oxidation resistance and corrosion resistance, which can enhance the chemical stability of catalysts at high potentials. Therefore, tungsten doped catalysts usually exhibit good stability during long-term operation, reducing catalyst deactivation and improving the sustainability of the reaction; (3) Adjusting surface structure: The addition of tungsten can regulate the electron density and geometric structure of the catalyst surface, optimizing the distribution of active sites. This phenomenon can enhance the interaction between the catalyst and reactants, reduce the activation energy of oxygen evolution reaction, and thus improve the reaction efficiency. 3.4 Overall water splitting performance Due to the dual functionality of HER and OER in the alkaline medium of W-CoMnP electrode, two identical W-CoMnP electrodes were used to create a dual electrode electrolysis cell for complete water splitting performance testing. In-situ Raman analysis was conducted using a self-made three electrode battery to determine the catalytic center and investigate the structural evolution during electrochemical activation. As shown in Fig. 7(a) , Raman spectra of W-CoMnP samples soaked in 1.0 mol/L NaOH solution were recorded at different voltages. During the application of voltage, the peak of W-CoMnP's Raman spectrum is caused by Co–O vibration, and its amorphous CoOOH peaks appear at 507.9 and 583.2 cm–1 [ 50,51 ]. This phenomenon also indicates that Co atoms on the surface of the material react with water molecules and oxygen in the atmosphere, ultimately forming the hydroxide oxide CoOOH. Applying voltage to the electrode will enhance the peak value of CoOOH. This result demonstrate that the potential provided to the electrode can accelerate the interaction between surface Co and OH–, oxygen or water. It is worth noting that the peaks at 507.9 and 583.2 cm–1 are attributed to CoOOH. When no voltage is applied, the peak value of CoOOH weakens; this peak is more pronounced and dominates at a potential of 1.5 V. When the applied potential decreases in sequence, the intensity of the peak also decreases again, indicating that the process is cyclically reversible [ 50 ]. Under the same testing conditions, analysis of the sample under a voltage of 1.5 V (Fig. 7(b)) reveals that the internal peaks contain more information (CoO2 at 457.7 cm–1, CoO at 640.1 cm–1, and Co3O4 at 721.2 cm–1). Based on the peak strength and peak area, it can be determined that the hydroxyl oxide CoOOH has a significant impact on the sample. Thus, the formation process of surface CoOOH was simulated (Fig. 7(c)). During the initial soaking process in alkaline solution, Co2+ ions and OH– ions on the surface of the material form a layered structure through hydrogen bonding. During electrochemical testing, layered cobalt hydroxide undergoes an oxidation reaction, resulting in a structural change and the formation of a new metastable hydroxide, namely cobalt hydroxide (CoOOH). Cobalt hydroxide is more active than cobalt oxide and is more suitable for electrocatalytic reactions under alkaline conditions. According to the crystal field theory [ 2 ], the valence electron configuration of Co is 3d and it has a high spin state (Fig. 7(d)). Therefore, it has unpaired electrons on the π-symmetric (t 2g) d orbital. In theory, it interacts with the orbital electrons of P through π symmetry. The e–1-e–1 repulsion is the main interaction between Mn2+/3+ species and P-orbital electrons, as the t 2g -d orbitals of low spin Mn2+ are completely occupied by electrons [ 2,38,51 ]. After coupling with Co and Mn2+, the e–1-e–1 repulsion between the orbital electrons of Mn2+ and P can be enhanced by Co–P to increase π symmetry. The result can accelerate the transfer of electrons on the catalyst surface and lead to negative orbital deviation, which can also be detected by XPS technology. To demonstrate the excellent electrocatalytic performance of W-CoMnP material, DFT calculations were conducted. Before calculation, the target samples were firstly constructed and optimized (Figs. S27 and S28) [ 52 ]. Typically, ideal HER catalysts have the lowest |ΔG H| values [ 38,52 ]. In Fig. 8(a) , the DFT calculation results indicate that compared to the other sample, W-CoMnP has only a weaker |ΔG H| energy (0.14 eV) than RuO2. By calculating and analyzing the adsorption free energies of OH*, OOH*, and O* in the basic structural processes, the potential Co and Mn active sites on the surface of W-CoMnP nanoclusters are elucidated using DFT method. For discrete units, Co is more likely to act as an active site. Fig. 8(b) depicts the optimized geometric models of W-CoMnP and the water oxidation process of CoMnP, indicating that OER is the key factor determining the reaction rate. The adsorption energy of intermediates made from oxygen is an objective benchmark for understanding the activity of the entire process of the OER mechanism (Fig. 8(g)). By utilizing the adsorption energy of intermediates generated by oxygen, it can be objectively revealed the activity of the entire process in the OER mechanism, and the entire process can be simulated. It is worth noting that the adsorption capacity of OER under intermediate conditions is inversely proportional to the energy barrier (ΔG) [ 52 ]. The process energy barriers of different materials under different U conditions are shown in Fig. 8. Compared with other materials, it is evident that W-CoMnP can successfully alter the four step G value (Fig. 8(c) and (d)). When the applied potential is 1.5 V, the absorption capacity of O* and OH* increases, resulting in a decrease in the ΔG value of W-CoMnP. The fourth process of CoMnP is the rate determining step (RDS). Due to the poor affinity of OOH* intermediates for Co site adsorption, the energy barrier (1.7 eV) for OOH* conversion to O2 is higher. However, the RDS energy barrier of W-CoMnP decreased to 1.5 eV, increasing the OOH* adsorption and lowering the energy threshold. According to theoretical evaluations, W doping can successfully reduce the energy barrier generated by intermediate states, improve OER activity and enhance mass transfer efficiency. These theoretical findings are similar to the experimental results. In order to gain a deeper understanding of the changes in interface electron distribution between OER intermediates and Co sites throughout the entire OER process, it is necessary to explore the direction of OOH* electron transfer [ 52,53 ]. When the two elements (Mn, P) coordinate with Co, electrons are more likely to move from Mn and P atoms to Co atoms due to the reason that their electronegativity is lower than that of Co. The 3D charge density difference plots in Figs. 8(e) and (f) further support this result, the positive charge of the P atom indicates that Co and Mn can capture electrons during the OER process. When W is doped into CoMnP structure, more electrons will rise from the metal reaction sites, attracting high valence metal species as active sites and accelerating the process of O2 production. Meanwhile, some electrons transfer from metal atoms to the generated OOH*. By comparison, it can be observed that the d-band centers of Co and Mn in samples with and without W doping have changed as shown in Figs. 9(a)–(d) . It is worth noting that compared to CoMnP without W doping, a rightward shift in the center of the Co atomic d-band can be observed in W-CoMnP sample. In the same situation, a significant rightward shift of the d-band center of Mn atoms remains unchanged. This phenomenon also indicates that the significant reaction rate of W-CoMnP is closely related to its increased adsorption affinity for intermediates. In the oxygen evolution reaction (OER) process, the external conditions of surface-active sites play a crucial role in promoting electron conversion and are largely influenced by their interaction with oxygen-containing intermediates. By integrating the projected density of states (PDOS) in W-CoMnP and CoMnP into the Fermi energy, the binding strength can be accurately analyzed [ 9,54 ]. As is well known, the ƒe value obtained by projecting the unsaturated coordination state is one of the key parameters for measuring OER activity. The calculated values of Co and Mn in the bimetallic phosphides W-CoMnP and CoMnP are 2.74, 2.43, 3.57 and 3.75, respectively (Figs. 9(e)–(h)). Excessive ƒe can lead to strong binding between W-CoMnP and oxygen-containing intermediates, resulting in a decrease in catalytic performance. On the contrary, lower ƒe will lead to weakened binding, which is also detrimental to catalytic efficiency. Therefore, having a suitable ƒe is the key to improve catalytic ability. Compared with CoMnP, the bimetallic phosphide W-CoMnP doped with W source exhibits excellent catalytic performance (Figs. 9(e)–(h)). For W-CoMnP, appropriately reducing the ƒe value not only ensures the binding between the catalyst and the intermediate, but also does not affect its catalytic performance after detachment. To gain a more thorough understanding of the electrocatalytic mechanism of W-CoMnP and to analyze its superior catalytic performance, DFT calculations were carried out on the target catalyst as well as other comparative samples. The corresponding results clearly indicate that compared with Mn3+ (Figs. 8(e) and (f)), Co2+ has more unfilled semi full orbitals, indicating that the interaction between Co and OER intermediates in W-CoMnP catalyst is more active. Clearly, upon the formation of nanoclusters, W-CoMnP tends to redistribute and accumulate electrons in the P 3p orbitals near the Co atoms, while fewer electrons are present around the P atoms due to Co's higher electronegativity, which causes this specific electron distribution. As a result of this characteristic, the metal atoms can attain higher valence states. The XPS results show that the orbital peaks of Co 2p 3/2 and 2p 1/2 are more prominent, which improved the overall water splitting efficiency. As one of the 3d orbital metals, Mn has various valence state changes with electrochemical activity typically occurring between +2 and +4 valences. The electronic configuration changes of Mn0/Mn2+/Mn3+/Mn4+ are shown in Fig. 9(k). The Mn-based catalyst, which shows relatively good performance in calculations, cannot maintain stability over long periods during electrochemical testing, primarily due to the Jahn-Teller effect. This effect, first introduced by Jahn and Teller in 1937, demonstrates that in degenerate electronic states, nonlinear molecular systems can experience persistent instability, leading to the elimination of degeneracy and the formation of new systems with lower symmetry and energy [ 29 ]. In nonlinear fields, octahedral Mn-based materials typically exhibit high-spin states of Mn3+, which have notable magnetism and cause pronounced Jahn-Teller distortions along the material's long axis (Fig. 9(i)). To alleviate degeneracy, octahedral complexes will undergo twisting along the z-axis. This phenomenon is observed in metal complexes with d orbitals, where degeneracy occurs when electrons occupy different orbitals that may possess the same or similar energy levels. In contrast to Mn3+ cations, Co and Ni cations do not exhibit selective Jahn-Teller distortions, which can be attributed to the serrated Jahn-Teller ordering along the elongated axis of Mn-based materials or the lack of electrons in the eg orbitals within the frameworks of Ni and Co-based materials [ 55 ]. Considering the influence of the electronic structure of materials, for 3d transition metals like Mn, the 3d orbitals are split into doubly degenerate eg orbitals (dx 2 -y 2 and dz 2) and triply degenerate t 2g orbitals (dxy , dxz , and dyz ) (Fig. 9(l)). In high-spin Mn3+ cations (t 2g 3 eg 1) within Mn-based materials, only one electron occupies an eg orbital (eg 1). The electrons on the dx 2- y 2 and dz 2 orbitals will cause varying degrees of shielding effects on the Mn nuclei in different directions [ 29,55–57 ]. In this configuration, the overall d orbital no longer matches the symmetry of the octahedron, resulting in instability of the central Mn3+ cation. The Mn3+ cation triggers a significant Jahn-Teller effect, leading to noticeable distortions in the local lattice structure and reducing electrochemical stability. A key approach to reduce Jahn-Teller distortion and improve the stability of Mn-based materials is by controlling the spin state (S) of Mn3+ ions. In the case of Mn3+, two possible spin configurations in W-CoMnP can occur: the high-spin state (t 2g 3 eg 1, S = 2) and the low-spin state (t 2g 4 eg 0, S = 1). Doping with W induces a transition of the Mn electron spin state to a low-spin configuration, where the Mn3+ electrons fully occupy all the t2g energy levels and transfer spin-reducing electrons (Fig. 9(j)). This effectively suppresses the Jahn-Teller effect of Mn3+ in CoMnP, allowing the material to display its catalytic properties. Experimental data and density functional theory (DFT) calculations jointly confirm that bimetallic phosphide nanocluster materials exhibit significant heterojunction behavior at higher electron density concentrations. This performance profoundly affects the electronic structure of W-CoMnP and is also an important manifestation of improving catalyst performance. Specifically, this modulation leads to the formation of coordination unsaturated Co and Mn atoms in the material matrix, which in turn become key sites for oxygen molecule capture, promoting the favorable synthesis of O–O bonds, which is a critical step in the oxygen evolution reaction (OER). Subsequently, the released O* atoms were captured by Co atoms embedded in the W-CoMnP lattice. By coordinating with adjacent Co atoms, the captured O* atoms exhibit active Co catalytic centers, particularly in higher spin electron states. Bader charge analysis supplemented these findings, indicating that throughout the OER process, the Co catalytic center gradually shifted towards higher oxidation states. The selective capture of OOH* intermediates from alkaline solutions is attributed to the presence of low-energy 3d orbitals that accommodate unpaired spin electrons. In the process of balancing CoNi-based catalysts and Mn-based catalysts (Fig. 10 ), Mn-based catalysts have multiple advantages of their own, however the Jahn Teller effect of Mn is a key issue restricting their development. Doping with metal W can effectively improve suppress the Jahn Teller effect and provide a new idea for designing Mn-based non precious metal water electrolysis catalysts. 4 Conclusions Overall, W-doped CoMn bimetallic phosphides can efficiently enhance the HER and OER electrocatalytic performance. Due to the doping of W source, the Jiang Taylor effect of Mn can be effectively suppressed, enhancing the stability of W-CoMnP material. Meanwhile, using in-situ Raman spectroscopy, it can be found that CoOOH is formed on the surface of the material during water electrolysis, which promotes the rearrangement and localization of electrons. At the same time, the negative shift of the d-band center of the active metal site in the medium optimizes the binding strength with HER related intermediates. The results indicate that under 1 mol/L KOH, W-CoMnP only requires a HER overpotential of 95 mV (η 10) and an OER overpotential of 225 mV (η 50). When W-CoMnP is used for overall water decomposition, it exhibits excellent stability, requiring just only 1.5 V (η 10). This work provides a new approach for the rational design and development of economically efficient bifunctional electrocatalysts, which has great practical value. coredata.dc:description: Manganese-based materials are influenced by the Jahn-Teller effect, causing the spontaneous dismutation of Mn3+ (2Mn3+ → Mn2+ + Mn4+) and the dissolution of Mn2+, which often results in diminished activity. This study uniquely employs a W doping strategy to suppress this effect. Externally, a simple template-free method was initially used to prepare cobalt- and manganese-based precursors, followed by a W doping process during the synthesis of transition bimetallic phosphides. Ultimately, W-doped bimetallic phosphides (W-CoMnP) were obtained. The W-CoMnP material demonstrates excellent HER and OER performance with low overpotentials of 95 mV (η₁₀ HER) and 225 mV (η₅₀ OER), and can achieve overall water splitting at a voltage of 1.52 V while maintaining stable cycling for 24 h. To enable commercial application, W-CoMnP was incorporated into an anion exchange membrane (AEM) electrolysis water device, demonstrating continuous and stable hydrogen production under ambient temperature conditions. This study offers a promising strategy for the future development of catalysts for AEM electrolysis water devices.
